# Pre-Development Check System

## Overview
This rule enforces mandatory checks before any code development or modifications. The Software Engineering Team (SET) must perform these checks before proceeding with any development work.

## Required Checks

### 1. Git Status Check
- Verify clean working directory
- Check for uncommitted changes
- Ensure on correct branch

### 2. Test Suite Status
- Run full test suite
- Verify all tests pass
- Check test coverage meets minimum requirements (50%)

### 3. Code Standards Check
# Note: PHPCS check is temporarily removed due to execution issues/timeouts.
# It should be reinstated once the underlying problems are resolved (See US-TD-005, US-TD-006, US-TD-007, US-TD-008)
# - Run PHP CodeSniffer
# - Verify PSR-12 compliance
# - Check WordPress coding standards

### 4. Dependency Check
- Verify composer.json is up to date
- Check for security vulnerabilities
- Ensure all required packages are installed

## Implementation Process

### Before Any Code Changes
```bash
# 1. Git Status Check
git status
git fetch origin
# Consider pulling changes from the main branch if necessary
# git pull origin [your-main-branch]

# 2. Test Suite Status
# Run PHPUnit tests using the configured bootstrap
# Adjust bootstrap path and options as needed per project
vendor/bin/phpunit --bootstrap [path/to/bootstrap.php]

# 3. Code Standards Check
# Ensure you are in the correct directory for the project/plugin being tested
# vendor/bin/phpcs --standard=WordPress .

# 4. Dependency Check
# Ensure you are in the correct directory for the project/plugin being tested
composer validate
composer install --dry-run # Check if updates are needed without installing
composer audit
```

### Failure Conditions
Development MUST NOT proceed if:
- Any tests are failing
# - Code standards checks fail
- Security vulnerabilities are found
- Dependencies are missing or invalid

### Error Resolution
1. Document all errors found
2. Fix each error before proceeding
3. Re-run all checks after fixes
4. Only proceed when all checks pass

## SET Response Protocol

When starting any development task, SET must:

1. Run the pre-development check script (excluding PHPCS for now)
2. Report results in the following format:
```
🟠 **Software Engineering Team (SET)**: Pre-development checks completed:
- Git Status: ✅ Clean
- Test Suite: ✅ All 157 tests passing
# - Code Standards: 🟡 SKIPPED (Known issue)
- Dependencies: ✅ All up to date
```

3. If any checks fail:
```
🟠 **Software Engineering Team (SET)**: Pre-development checks failed:
- Git Status: ❌ Uncommitted changes present
- Test Suite: ❌ 2 tests failing
# - Code Standards: 🟡 SKIPPED (Known issue)
- Dependencies: ❌ Security vulnerability found

Action Required: Must resolve all issues before proceeding with development.
```

## Integration with Cursor

This rule requires SET to:
1. Run checks before any file modifications (excluding PHPCS for now)
2. Report check results in all responses
3. Refuse to proceed with development if checks fail
4. Document any failures and required fixes 